http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/karnataka/Body-of-infant-exhumed-autopsy-report-awaited/article14005487.ece

The body of 18-month-old Srujan, who died after a pharmacist gave him injections for a fever, was exhumed in Hulgunda village, near Kushalnagar, on Monday, and a post-mortem was conducted.The autopsy was conducted by forensic medicine experts from the Mysore Medical College and Research Institute (MMC&RI) in the presence of officials and the parents of the child, after which the body was buried again.The child had died at the government hospital in Madikeri on January 11, days after Ganapati, a pharmacist in Koppa, administered injections without a qualified doctor’s prescription. “The post-mortem report is awaited,” Deputy Superintendent of Police, Hunsur, Harish Pande told The Hindu.Sources in MMC&RI said that the sample of the skin, where the injections had been given, and other routine samples were collected for pathological and forensic laboratory examination.The post-mortem report, which is likely to be submitted to the police in three or four days, is expected to throw light on the cause of the boy’s death. “We have to ascertain whether the antibiotics administered by the pharmacist led to the child’s death,” a medical expert said.The parents — Mohan and Kokila — both agricultural labourers, took their sick child to ‘Deshik Medicals’, Ganapati’s pharmacy in Koppa, about 8 km from their village, on January 3.The police said the nearest primary health centre from Hulgunda village was situated in Kushalnagar, about 9 km away. Ganapati, an ex-serviceman, who was known as a “military doctor” in the area, allegedly administered him injections on three days — January 3, 5 and 7. The infant developed complications and died on January 11. His parents lodged a complaint at the Bylakuppe police station on January 16, leading to the arrest of Ganapati.We have to ascertain whether the antibiotics administered by the pharmacist led to the child’s deathMedical expert